<TEXT>
<P>
A tax on telephone customers to subsidize service for low-income households in 
California is being cut by the state Public Utilities Commission. Effective 
July 1, the tax will fall to 2.5% of a customer's charges for in-state toll 
calls, down from 4%. The tax is used to reduce charges for the 1.3 million 
customers receiving what is known as Lifeline service to half the normal rate. 
The tax reduction was prompted by a surplus in the fund that pays for Lifeline 
service. 
