</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
One of three men who kidnaped and buried a bus full of schoolchildren 13 years 
ago has been denied a parole for the 10th time. Richard Schoenfeld, 35, who is 
serving a life sentence, is still a danger to society, a Board of Prison Terms 
panel decided. Schoenfeld was convicted for his role in the Chowchilla 
kidnaping of 26 schoolchildren and their driver from the rural San Joaquin 
Valley town for $5 million ransom. Schoenfeld, his brother, James, and 
Frederick N. Woods commandeered the bus on July 15, 1976, and took it 100 miles 
to Livermore. There they shut the victims in a poorly ventilated moving van 
buried in a quarry. It took the group 16 hours to dig to safety through the 
wood- and earth-covered hole. 
