<HEADLINE>
<P>
INSURANCE UNITS OF IRVINE-BASED LINCOLN TO BE SOLD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JAMES S. GRANELLI, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Federal regulators said Thursday they plan to sell the major insurance 
operation of Irvine-based Lincoln Savings &amp; Loan to a Dallas investment 
firm for an undisclosed price. 
</P>
<P>
The insurance operation is part of a Lincoln subsidiary that filed for 
bankruptcy April 13, along with Lincoln's parent company, American Continental 
Corp., and 10 other S&amp;L subsidiaries. Lincoln was seized by regulators the 
next day. 
</P>
<P>
Regulators said they intend to sell Continental Fidelity Insurance Co. and its 
operating unit, American Founders Life Insurance Co., to Zlogar &amp; Co. 
</P>
<P>
Zlogar had been negotiating with Phoenix-based American Continental to purchase 
the insurance operation before American Continental filed Chapter 11 bankruptcy 
petition. Under the petitions, executives at American Continental remain in 
control of the holding company, but regulators control the Lincoln 
subsidiaries. 
</P>
<P>
The purchase price in the current deal was not revealed, but it is all cash and 
higher than the value of the cash-and-notes deal that Zlogar had worked out 
with American Continental, said Al Zlogar, the Dallas company's president. The 
value of the previous deal was a little less than $45 million, he said. 
</P>
<P>
The deal still must be approved by the U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Phoenix because 
the insurance operations are owned directly by the Amcor Funding Corp. 
subsidiary. 
</P>
<P>
"We're elated," Zlogar said. "The insurance companies are healthy and rated 
A-excellent by A.M. Best Co. (an industry rating firm). We intend to maintain 
that rating or better it." 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Operates in 23 States 
</P>
<P>
The decision to buy the insurance operation, he said, was "95% based on the 
management of company." He said he was "very impressed" with current managers, 
who would remain in place after the purchase and help expand the company. 
</P>
<P>
American Founders, with $300 million in assets, is licensed in 37 states and 
operates in 23. 
</P>
<P>
Mark M. Connally, an American Continental spokesman, said it was too early to 
know if the company would object to the proposed sale. 
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, American Continental outlined a plan to work its way out of 
bankruptcy. The plan includes the transfer of Amcor to a new holding company 
owned by American Continental executives. 
</P>
<P>
"We have not seen the terms of the sale, so we don't know yet if it will impact 
our proposal," Connally said. "However, at this point, our plan will have 
serious viability with or without American Founders Life." 
</P>
<P>
Amcor's other major asset is its 20% stake in General Oriental Investments 
Ltd., an offshore international investment firm headed by British financier Sir 
James Goldsmith. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Full Run 
</P>
</TYPE>
