<P>
TRUCK SPILLS PESTICIDES IN VALENCIA, CAUSING MASSIVE TRAFFIC JAM ON I-5 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and wire service reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Traffic on the Golden State Freeway backed up for miles in each direction in 
Valencia this morning after a pickup truck overturned and spilled possibly 
dangerous liquid and powder pesticides on the roadway. 
</P>
<P>
The accident, which closed six of the eight lanes of the freeway, occurred 
about 3 a.m. a mile north of Valencia Boulevard. A northbound pickup driven by 
Anthony Roy Canton, 24, of Hollywood went out of control and overturned, the 
California Highway Patrol said. 
</P>
<P>
The truck was carrying several types of industrial pesticides. Four containers 
spilled onto the roadway before the truck came to a rest on the center divider, 
CHP Officer Ralph Elvira said. 
</P>
<P>
The CHP closed three lanes on each side of the freeway while a hazardous 
materials team from the Los Angeles County Fire Department responded. Traffic 
slowed to a crawl in the one lane left open in each direction. 
</P>
<P>
An additional lane was opened in each direction shortly after 7 a.m., but 
thousands of commuters were caught in a traffic jam that stretched north toward 
Castaic and south to Lyons Avenue. The remaining closed lanes of the freeway 
were being reopened at about noon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
