<P>
HAWKE WEEPS OVER CHINA VIOLENCE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
CANBERRA, Australia 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Prime Minister Bob Hawke burst into tears during a memorial service today as he 
described the brutal shooting of civilians in China by the military. 
</P>
<P>
"I call on the Chinese government to withdraw its troops from deployment 
against unarmed civilians and to respect the will of its people," Hawke told 
1,000 people at the service in the Great Hall of the federal Parliament. 
</P>
<P>
Hawke tearfully read eyewitness reports of the killings, saying anti-personnel 
carriers and tanks "ran backwards and forwards over the bodies of the slain 
until they were reduced to pulp." 
</P>
<P>
Hawke has cried openly several times in public, once during debate in 
Parliament on Israel and earlier this year when admitting on television that he 
had committed adultery. At that time he said he still loved his wife, Hazel, 
calling her an "incredible woman." 
</P>
