<HEADLINE>
<P>
P. M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
DOCK WALKOUTS SPREAD IN BRITAIN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
LONDON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Wildcat walkouts by dockworkers spread today to at least six ports throughout 
Britain as workers protested a court ruling banning a national strike. 
</P>
<P>
About 2,500 dockworkers have joined in the unofficial action, a spokesman for 
the Transport and General Workers' Union said. 
</P>
<P>
The TGWU represents 9,400 dockworkers. Union officials have urged striking 
workers to go back to work while the union appeals the injunction to the Law 
Lords, Britain's highest court. 
</P>
<P>
According to union officials and a spokeswoman for the National Assn. of Port 
Employers, dockworkers have walked off the job at Liverpool, Bristol, 
Lowestoft, Great Yarmouth, Garston near Liverpool and Tilbury in London. 
</P>
