<HEADLINE>
<P>
KLEIN TO QUIT RACING, SELL ALL HIS 146 HORSES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SAN DIEGO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Eugene V. Klein, three-time Eclipse Award winner as North America's leading 
thoroughbred owner, is getting out of horse racing, he said today. 
</P>
<P>
Among the 146 horses Klein will sell are 1988 Kentucky Derby winner Winning 
Colors, 1986 Horse of the Year Lady's Secret and current 3-year-old filly Open 
Mind. 
</P>
<P>
"I guess it's just the time of my life and the stage of life that I'm at," the 
68-year old former owner of the San Diego Chargers said. "All my life I have 
been very, very competitive -- since the days of flying for the Air Force in 
World War II. 
</P>
<P>
"There comes a time you should do what you want to do and take it easy." 
</P>
<P>
In addition to the stars of his stable, Klein's stock of brood mares, 
yearlings, foals of 1989 and horses in training will be disposed of at the 
two-day November Breeding Stock Sale at Keeneland in Lexington, Ky. 
</P>
<P>
Since entering the thoroughbred business in 1982, Klein has raced six champions 
in his name or in partnership, won seven Breeders' Cup races and 11 Eclipse 
Awards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
